<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Olla System for Vacation Watering Outdoors</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    One pot works for a plant — a system works for a garden.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, the best olla system is a network of properly spaced, correctly sized ollas that provide overlapping moisture zones for consistent coverage.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    A single olla can keep one plant alive. But outdoor gardens — especially beds — need a system that distributes water evenly over time.
  </p>
  <p>
    The difference between success and failure usually comes down to spacing, capacity, and planning.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Actually Works?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> multiple ollas spaced for full coverage.</li>
      <li><strong>Best feature:</strong> overlapping moisture zones.</li>
      <li><strong>Best priority:</strong> matching system capacity to time away.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    Coverage matters more than individual pot size.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How an Olla System Works</h2>

  <p>
    Each olla creates a localized moisture zone as water seeps into the surrounding soil. A system connects these zones so plants receive consistent moisture across the entire area.
  </p>

  <p>
    This results in:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>more even soil hydration</li>
    <li>reduced dry spots</li>
    <li>better plant stability during absence</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The goal is continuity, not isolated watering points.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Single Ollas Fail in Outdoor Setups</h2>

  <p>
    A single olla only hydrates a limited radius. In larger beds:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>plants outside the zone dry out</li>
    <li>soil moisture becomes uneven</li>
    <li>watering becomes unpredictable</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A system solves this by expanding coverage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Olla System</h2>

  <h3>Proper Spacing</h3>
  <p>
    Ensures moisture zones overlap without leaving gaps.
  </p>

  <h3>Correct Pot Size</h3>
  <p>
    Matches plant density and soil volume.
  </p>

  <h3>Sufficient Total Capacity</h3>
  <p>
    Lasts the entire time you’re away.
  </p>

  <h3>Consistent Installation Depth</h3>
  <p>
    Aligns moisture zones with root systems.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Spacing: The Most Important Factor</h2>

  <p>
    Olla systems fail most often due to poor spacing. Too far apart, and dry zones develop. Too close, and space is wasted.
  </p>

  <p>
    In general:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>spacing should allow moisture zones to overlap slightly</li>
    <li>denser plantings require closer spacing</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Think in terms of coverage, not individual pots.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Capacity Planning for Vacation Use</h2>

  <p>
    Total water capacity must match:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>number of plants</li>
    <li>weather conditions</li>
    <li>length of absence</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Underestimating capacity is the most common failure point.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Olla Systems Work Best</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>raised beds</strong></li>
    <li><strong>in-ground garden rows</strong></li>
    <li><strong>moderate-sized outdoor setups</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    They’re most effective in structured planting layouts.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where They Fall Short</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>very large gardens</strong></li>
    <li><strong>long vacations without refilling</strong></li>
    <li><strong>extreme heat conditions</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Scaling limits their effectiveness.
  </p>
</section>

